column213: She has  been tolerating well the therapy until last week when she was noted to have  more sluggish activity level. Her mother reports that she could not take  her last day of R115777. Her mother also reports that  she has had increased number of accidents, 4 times per day of urinary  incontinence. Her last bowel movement was on Saturday. FINDINGS: There has been an interval increase in the overall extent and  enhancement of the diffuse pontine tumor. It measures approximately 3  .8 cm AP x 6.0 cm TV x 6.0 cm SI compared to 3.3 cm AP x 4.8 cm TV x  5.2 cm SI on the prior exam. Scattered foci of susceptibility artifact  within the tumor are consistent with small foci of intratumoral  hemorrhage and less likely mineralization. The tumor extends exophytically into the prepontine cistern  and protrudes posteriorly into the fourth ventricle.  There is increased mass effect on the fourth ventricle. Superiorly, it  extends to the middle cerebral peduncles, left greater than right.  Inferiorly, the tumor extends to the upper medulla. Posteriorly, it  extends into the middle cerebellar peduncles. There is increased  extension into the cerebral and cerebellar peduncles since the prior  study, and right cerebellar hemisphere now. On the post contrast images, there is increased enhancement of  the dorsal portions of the tumor. The lateral and third ventricles  have increased in size since the prior study. On diffusion weighted  imaging there are no areas of restricted diffusion. Incidental note  is made of a small pineal cyst.    There is bilateral maxillary sinus mucosal thickening, which almost completely occupies these sinuses as well as mucosal thickening completely filling the right sphenoid sinus; these findings have increased since the prior exam.    IMPRESSION: Interval increase in the extent and enhancement of the pontine glioma as described. Interval increase in paranasal sinus disease.

column110: six-year-old boy with a diffuse pontine glioma which was diagnosed in October 2006 when he was 4 years old. He had been previously healthy until he presented with ataxia, tripping while walking, frequent falling and facial asymmetry. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) revealed a pontine lesion. He was treated with 6 weeks of radiation therapy and chemotherapy.  He responded well and in January 2007. However, in May 2007 he had progression by MRI and so was started on second therapeutic regimen with Avastin and Irinotecan. He subsequently had progression on MRI in November and his chemotherapy regimen was changed. He received one dose of Tensirolomus however he had a severe allergic reaction and so began Temozolimide on December 26, 2007.  Again Edwin has had progressive symptoms and an MRI on January 5, 2008 confirmed disease progression for which he received Temozolomide from February 4 to 8. On February 27 another MRI showed findings consistent with tumor progression, particularly within the brain stem, the right temporal lobe, and the left thalamus as well as  worsening hydrocephalus and trans ependymal flow of CSF. This, as well as condition and prognosis, was discussed with his parents. It was decided not to give any further therapy that would require hospitalization, to discontinue all tubes or machines, and not to resuscitate in event of an arrest. He was discharged to hospice services on Ativan and morphine.  While in hospice on Saturday March 15 at approximately 10 a.m. began to have labored breathing and passed away.

column149: MRI OF THE BRAIN 9/6/00    HISTORY:  Patient is a five year old female with history of pontine glioma, x-ray and thalidomide therapy.     TECHNIQUE:  MR of the brain was performed using sagittal T1, sagittal T2, axial T2 and FLAIR, echo planar diffusion imaging, perfusion imaging, and MR spectroscopy. Post-Gadolinium axial and coronal T1 weighted images were obtained through the brain.    MR spectroscopy was performed by placing the voxel over the area of signal abnormality in the pons, which included part of the anterior right cerebellum. This MR spectroscopy dictation has been dictated as a separate order number.    FINDINGS:  The current exam is compared with previous study of 7/5/00. Compared with this previous study, there is now increased T2 signal identified in the right pons inferiorly. Dimensions of the signal abnormality measured on T2 weighted images are 1.1 cm (AP) x 1.0 cm (transverse), and 1.2 cm in the craniocaudal dimension. This definitely represents a change compared with previous study. Following Gadolinium administration, there is enhancement of a slightly exophytic component, which projects into the prepontine cistern adjacent to the right vertebral artery. There are no other areas of signal abnormality in the brain and there are no other areas of abnormal enhancement.     There is probably increased diffusion in the tumor.  MR spectroscopy was performed by placing the voxel over the area of pontine signal abnormality which included some of the anterior right cerebellar parenchyma. Previously identified was increased T2 signal in the left mastoid antral air cells. This signal abnormality in the left mastoid air cells is more pronounced today and more confluent.    IMPRESSION:    1) Increased signal abnormality in the right pons compared with the previous study. There is some enhancement of a slightly exophytic in the prepontine cistern near the right vertebral artery.   2) Left mastoid fluid signal.

column222: technically progressed on 10/6/00, but didn't start treatment until after this MRI - was watching    MR OF THE BRAIN, 10/6/00    HISTORY:  This is a 6-year-old female with history of brain stem glioma.  Has received x-ray therapy and is on thalidomide therapy.  The oncologist reports that the x-ray therapy was performed prior to the most recent last scan of 9/6/00.    TECHNIQUE:  MR of the brain was performed using sagittal T1, axial T2 and FLAIR, sagittal T2, and post-gadolinium sagittal and axial images through the brain.  High-resolution axial images were obtained using 3 mm slice thickness with a 1 mm skip between sections.    FINDINGS:  The current exam is compared with the most recent prior MR of 9/6/00.  There has been considerable change in the appearance of the brain stem when compared to that prior study.  Today, there is more signal abnormality identified within the lower pons and upper medulla, particularly on the right.  There is signal abnormality within the right pons at the level of the right middle cerebellar peduncle extending caudad to the upper medulla.  Again, there is a slightly exophytic component of the tumor extending near the right vertebral artery.  The amount of exophytic tumor appears increased on T2-weighted images relative to the September 6, 2000 study.  Also on the conventional images, there is slightly greater mass effect on the right aspect of the fourth ventricle.  The lateral and third ventricles are slightly larger.  Today, the T2 signal abnormality in the brainstem measures 4.0 cm. (CC) x 1.8 cm (AP) x 2.5 cm (TV) in greatest dimension.    Following administration of gadolinium, there is increased enhancement of the brainstem in the area of the T2 signal abnormality and increased tumor identified in the right prepontine cistern.  Also, there is new enhancement in the upper right medulla and right aspect of the pons which was not present on the prior study.      IMPRESSION:  1) Findings suggest lateral tumor growth with increased exophytic tumor in the right prepontine cistern.   There is increased enhancement suggesting progression of tumor.   2) The left mastoid air cells are fluid-filled as they were on the 9/6/00 study.  3) The pontine portion of the tumor is exhibiting slight increased mass effect with some compression of the right aspect of the fourth ventricle inferiorly with minimal increase in the lateral ventricular size.

column27: FINDINGS: There is a large, heterogeneous, and partially cystic mass in the  left posterior parietal region, measuring approximately 5.6 cm (AP) x 5.9 cm (  SI) x 5.1 cm (TRV). column26: Specimen #1, labeled "Thalamic mass" (including 1FSA, 1SMA):    	-  Poorly differentiated malignant neoplasm most consistent with GLIOBLASTOMA (W.H.O. Grade IV/IV; ICD-0 9440/3).  See Note.    Specimen #2, labeled "More thalamic mass":    	-  Poorly differentiated malignant neoplasm most consistent with GLIOBLASTOMA (W.H.O. Grade IV/IV; ICD-0 9440/3).  See Note.    Specimen #3, labeled "Canister suction of thalamic tumor contents":    	-  Poorly differentiated malignant neoplasm most consistent with GLIOBLASTOMA (W.H.O. Grade IV/IV; ICD-0 9440/3).  See Note.    COMMENT:  This anaplastic and very mitotically active infiltrating lesion is focally, but clearly, immunoreactive for GFAP.  What is unusual for glioma is cell size, considerably larger than is typical, with the degree of nuclear molding.  These features are more consistent with high grade ("anaplastic") neuronal tumor or PNET, but synaptophysin staining is negative, and GFAP is positive. Olig2 is distinctly positive, but I have no experience with this antibody."    INTERPRETATION:  Cytogenetic analysis reveals thirteen mitotic cells from 7-8 day adherent cultures of this brain tumor specimen are characterized by near-triploidy, with numerical and structural abnormalities.  Two cells are polyploids of the original clone.  Five cells contained an apparently normal karyotype, with no evidence of clinically significant numerical or structural chromosome abnormalities.    The i(17q) is commonly associated with medulloblastoma/PNET of the CNS.    Update:  Per Dr. Folkerth the pathology is most consistent with glioblastoma.  While i(17q) is highly associated with medulloblastoma it is not an uncommon finding in other brain tumors, especially when a complex karyotype is present, such as glioblastoma."
column27: BRAIN: There is a large, rounded, mass lesion centered in the right thalamus,  measuring 4.0 cm (TV) x 5.3 cm (AP) x 40 cm (SI).  Susceptability is seen throughout the lesion and the heterogenous T1 and T2  signal intensity indicates hemorrage in various stages of evolution. T2  prolongation extends inferiorly into the left midbrain and inferolaterally  around the temporal horn. Although there are pockets of restricted diffusion  within this lesion, the lesion is hemorrhagic; there is minimal restricted  diffusion along the margins of the lesion. After contrast was given, there is a  thick linear focus of enhancement that can be followed from the lateral  posterior aspect of the lesion superiorly medially.    The lesion causes compression and shift of the midbrain to the left and the  right basal ganglia anteriorly. The internal cerebral veins and other veins are  displaced by the lesion. Branches of the right posterior cerebral artery are  displaced. There is overall mass effect on the brainstem which is as a result  located more anteriorly, and the cerebellar tonsils come up to the foramen  magnum. There is compression on the body and atria of the right lateral  ventricle and third ventricle with approximately 8 mm right to left midline  shift. There is asymmetric dilation of the anterior and temporal horns of the  right lateral ventricle with intraventricular hemorrhage layering in the  occipital horns of the bilateral lateral ventricles, greater on the right. A  ventricular catheter is in place via a left frontal approach with the tip in  the anterior horn of the left lateral ventricle.    MRA: The right middle cerebral artery is inferior and lateral to the lesion and  the right posterior cerebral artery is displaced slightly inferiorly. On the  MRA, all vessels of the circle of Willis arepatent with normal contour and no  evidence of occlusion or encasement . No aneurysm is indentified. There is no  evidence that un underlying AVM exists.

column26: NOTES:  .  The histologic features, GFAP-positivity, mitoses, and focally high MIB-1 proliferative index (13%) seen in specimen #5 are consistent with an ANAPLASTIC ASTROCYTOMA.  Extensive confluent regions of necrosis and intense acute inflammation are noted which could represent infarction of tumor or infection (though there is no evidence of micro-organisms on special stains); its significance is unknown and it is therefore not used as a diagnostic grading criterion in this case.    Dr. Anthony has reviewed the case and is of the opinion that this tumor is best classified as a malignant astrocytoma.

column26: NOTES:  This neoplasm is poorly-differentiated, with the only evidence of specific differentiation being the presence of processes at the light and electron microscopic level and faint focal immunoreactivity for GFAP, findings which support a tumor of glial (or astrocytic) differentiation. column21: There is a predominantly T2 hyperintense mass in the left parietal lobe which measures approximately 3.4 x 2.8 x 1.9 cm (anterior AP x RL x SI).  Surrounding this is extensive T2 hyperintensity in the white matter.  There is extension of similar signal into the thalamus on the left which has rounded margins.  There is also abnormal signal within the majority of the left frontal lobe.  Additionally, there is abnormal T2 hyperintensity in the medial cortex of the right frontal lobe.  There is mild midline shift at the level of the basal ganglia.  There is no hydrocephalus.  There are normal flow voids in the region of the circle of Willis included in the right anterior cerebral artery.  MRS demonstrates marked increase in the choline/NAA ratio.  There is also a large lactate peak.  Diffusion-weighted imaging demonstrates increased diffusion in the center of the mass and restricted diffusion at the periphery.  These findings are consistent with tumor.  Perfusion imaging demonstrates increased perfusion in portions of the tumor as well.    Imaging of the spine demonstrated no abnormal enhancement.    IMPRESSION:    1. High-grade tumor with the center in the left parietal lobe with extension anteriorly into the left frontal lobe and extensive surrounding T2 changes.  There is also abnormal signal in the medial right frontal cortex.  This is most consistent with a high-grade glial tumor, likely gliomatosis cerebri.  2. No hydrocephalus.  3. No evidence of metastasis to the spine.
column26: FINAL DIAGNOSIS:  .  Specimens #1, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 1FSA);            #2, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 2FSA);            #3, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 3FSA);            #4, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 4FSA)            #5, labeled "Occipital tumor":      -  HIGH-GRADE (ANAPLASTIC), INFILTRATING GLIOMA with focal ependymal      differentiation.  See note.    Specimen #6, labeled "Dura":   .    -  Fragments of dura mater with adherent ANAPLASTIC GLIOMA.  See note.    Specimen #7, labeled "Tissue in suction container":      -  Fragments of ANAPLASTIC GLIOMA consistent with specimens #1-5.    NOTES:  Overall, the findings in this case are that of a diffusely infiltrative high grade glioma with heterogeneous histology.  The infiltrative nature is consistent with reported appearance on neurimaging. In some areas it has recognizable ependymal differentiation. In these areas GFAP labelling is weak, and there is NeuN labelling, which has been reported in ependymoma (Parker et.al. found NeuN labelling in 13/20 ependymal lesions and of these 9 were anaplastic ependymomas).  Although frank invasion may rarely be seen in the anaplastic ependymomas the appearance in many regions is not ependymal and is more consistent with infiltrating glial neoplasm.  Mitoses are present and the MIB-1 index is elevated.     This case was reviewed by Dr.U.DeGirolami who commented that "this is basically an ependymoma with anaplastic features, i.e. mitoses, high MIB-1, and sheetlike growth".

He presented to the Emergency Room in December 2016 with a several months of headaches.  Imaging showed increased ventricular size with stable tumor.  Shunt exploration and ventricular catheter obstruction clearance  December 25, 2016.  He did well, however, the weekend of April 6, 2017, he developed headaches and was seen in the Emergency Room. Underwent revision of the right occipital ventriculoperitoneal shunt on April 6, 2017, as well as placement of a new ventricular catheter.  He had a subsequent shunt revision on 5/21/2017 which included exchange of the proximal catheter.  This was his last revision.  He has since been followed with surveillance imaging.  Prior to his most recent hospitalization his last MRI brain was in August 28, 2021 which showed some scattered areas of enhancing nodularity within the posterior fossa which were unchanged when compared to November 2019 scan.  He was last seen by neurosurgery in September 2021 after that scan.      With regards to his most recent hospitalization, he presented on 10/5/2021 in the setting of altered mental status, left eye deviation, with left arm posturing and potentially shaking movements.  He was initially taken to an outside hospital where he underwent CT head and CTA which showed normal appearance of the ventricles and no acute hemorrhage.  During the evaluation, he developed a generalized tonic-clonic seizure for which she received Ativan 2 mg, followed by a second generalized tonic-clonic seizure for which she received a second dose of Ativan 2 mg. He was then transferred to Boston children's for further evaluation.  On transfer, he was noted to have declining mental status with evidence of decreased movement of his extremities.  He received Keppra bolus of 60 mg/kg and was intubated for airway protection.  He was subsequently started on Keppra maintenance at 1000 mg twice daily.  He underwent an MRI brain with MRA and MRV head, which showed no interval changes with no vessel occlusion or thrombus.  He had EEG monitoring which showed slowing but no evidence of seizures.  He had a shunt tap to evaluate for infection and CSF showed no pleocytosis with a negative culture.  Toxicology screen was also sent and positive for cannabinoids.  He was extubated the next day and transferred to the neurology service.  His mental status improved back to baseline.  Overall impression was that marijuana use had triggered a first-time seizure in the setting of increased susceptibility to seizures given his tumor and surgical history.

column222: Not really a progression but development of a new glioma. Radiation was administered from February 19, 1997, until March 31, 1997. Post-radiation therapy, he developed moyamoya disease and underwent bilateral pial synangiosis. An MRI/MRA on August 26, 1998, revealed an increase in the right optic tract cyst, but otherwise stability. A followup MRI May 19, 2001, showed a decrease in the size of the right temporal cystic component of the optic glioma, but worsening abnormal signal involving the right temporal lobe. At that point, he continued to be observed. In May 2002, imaging revealed a new aneurysm involving the right M1 segment, which also was observed. An MRI from February 23, 2006, revealed increase in the cerebellar lesion for which he underwent treatment with vincristine and actinomycin D. He developed significant neurotoxicity foot drop related to the vincristine and so he received single-agent actinomycin, which was completed in July 2007. End of treatment MRI scan revealed near resolution of the cerebellar lesion. Ongoing interval MRIs have shown a slow increase in the enhancing area involving the right cerebellum and stable moyamoya disease. We have reviewed Michael's images at our brain tumor conferences and the consensus was in the absence of any clinical symptoms to continue with observation.
